## Branch Strategy

### Structure

```
master        ← stable, released versions only
dev           ← main development branch
feature/*     ← new mechanics and systems
fix/*         ← bug fixes
data/*        ← balance/content-only changes
refactor/*    ← code cleanup without new functionality
ci/*          ← CI/CD changes
```

### When to Create Branches

| Branch | When | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `feature/*` | Any new system or mechanic | `feature/combat-poison-effect` |
| `fix/*` | Fixing a specific bug | `fix/archer-targeting` |
| `data/*` | Data/balance changes only, no logic | `data/warrior-rebalance` |
| `refactor/*` | Code cleanup only | `refactor/targeting-system` |
| `ci/*` | CI/CD or build pipeline changes | `ci/add-test-workflow` |

### Rules

- All branches are created **from `dev`**, never from `master`
- `master` is updated only via PR from `dev` — when the version is stable
- Branch names: lowercase, hyphen-separated, concise
  - Good: `feature/guild-management`
  - Bad: `feature/add_new_guild_management_system`
- No broken compilation in any commit
- Delete branches after merging
- Keep `dev` always green and buildable: do breaking/WIP work on `feature/*`, merge into `dev` only when CI is green
- `CI Gate` is the required status check on `dev` and `master`; docs/wiki/markdown pass instantly, code requires green tests

### When you MUST create a branch (never commit directly to `dev`)

If currently on `dev` or `master`, **always** create a branch before starting:
- Any new feature, system, or mechanic (`feature/*`)
- Mass bug fixing or large fix affecting multiple files (`fix/*`)
- Refactoring (`refactor/*`)
- Any change that touches ≥3 files or takes more than one commit

**Exceptions — allowed directly on `dev`:**
- Hotfix: tiny, isolated fix (1-2 files, obvious change, no risk of breaking CI)
- Docs/wiki-only changes
- CI/config tweaks with no logic changes

---

## Releases (Tags)

Testable/release versions are pinned with **tags**, not a separate branch.

- Tag format: `vMAJOR.MINOR.PATCH` (e.g. `v0.1.0`); milestones get a suffix (`v0.1.0-festival`)
- Tag a stable commit (usually on `master`, after a PR from `dev`)
- Build/test any version anytime: `git checkout <tag>` → build. Pin Steam builds to tags for reproducibility
- A `release/*` branch is created **only** when parallel stabilization is needed (freeze a release while `dev` keeps moving) — usually unnecessary for solo
